90, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Maitland was born in 1470, in Caithness, Scotland, his father, Robert Maitland, was 35 and his mother, Maria Scrymshire, was 30. He had at least 2 sons with Elspeth Douglas. He died in 1550, in Auckingill, Caithness, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 80, and was buried in Auckingill, Caithness, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1470–1550":"1470–1550","1477–1573":"1477–1573","1499–Male":"1499–Surnud","1501–1599":"1501–1599","1435–Male":"1435–Surnud","1440–Female":"1440–Surnud","1501":"1501","1435":"1435","1599":"1599","1499":"1499","1455":"1455","1477":"1477","1573":"1573","1550":"1550","1440":"1440","1470":"1470","Auchingill, , Caithness, Scotland":"Auckingill, Caithness, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Caithness, Scotland":"Caithness, Scotland"},"fi":{"1470–1550":"1470–1550","1477–1573":"1477–1573","1499–Male":"1499–Kuollut","1501–1599":"1501–1599","1435–Male":"1435–Kuollut","1440–Female":"1440–Kuollut","1501":"1501","1435":"1435","1599":"1599","1499":"1499","1455":"1455","1477":"1477","1573":"1573","1550":"1550","1440":"1440","1470":"147